<paragraph id="470F36E8E957ED664353FAD0CF13713D" blockId="63.[820,1102,1333,1358]" box="[820,1102,1333,1358]" pageId="63" pageNumber="63">
<heading id="1C478184E957ED664353FAD0CF13713D" box="[820,1102,1333,1358]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="63" pageNumber="63" reason="4">
FAMILY 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE957ED6643FDFAD3CF13713D" authorityName=", sensu Yeates" authorityYear="1994" box="[922,1102,1333,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">BOMBYLIIDAE</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="470F36E8E957ED1942BFFA81CAF077C0" blockId="63.[696,1224,1383,1738]" lastBlockId="64.[119,650,226,1539]" lastPageId="64" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="63" pageNumber="63">
This is a large, heterogeneous family of asiloid flies that are ecologically important as larval parasitoids and adult pollinators, especially in Mediterranean biomes. They range from minute, empidoidlike 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE957ED66430DFA0DCF747273" authorityName="Melander" authorityYear="1902" box="[874,1065,1515,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Mythicomyiinae">Mythicomyiinae</taxonomicName>
(sometimes placed in their own family), to very large, striking 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE957ED664282F9CBC8337235" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1804" box="[741,878,1581,1605]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Anthracinae">Anthracinae</taxonomicName>
with bold color patterns. 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E957ED6644F0F9CBC85C7217" author="Hull, F. M." pageId="63" pageNumber="63" refId="ref58365" refString="Hull, F. M. 1973. Bee flies of the world: the genera of the family Bombyliidae. Washington: Smithsonian Institution Press." type="book" year="1973">Hull (1973)</bibRefCitation>
monographed the world genera, comprised of some 4500 species, and summarized the biology, morphology, fossils, and zoogeography. Beeflies are efficient pollinators of diverse herbaceous angiosperms (e.g., Grimaldi, 1988; 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED19401FFEE5CA43756B" author="Herrera, J." box="[120,286,259,283]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="274 - 287" refId="ref58290" refString="Herrera, J. 1988. Pollination relationships in southern Spanish Mediterranean shrublands. Journal of Ecology 76 (1): 274 - 287." type="journal article" year="1988">Herrera, 1988</bibRefCitation>
; Pentadinous and Ellis, 1993; Goldblatt and Manning, 2000; 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED194180FEC2CA58752D" author="Kastinger, C. &amp; A. Weber" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="3 - 25" refId="ref58451" refString="Kastinger, C., and A. Weber. 2001. Bee-flies (Bombylius spp., Bombyliidae, Diptera) and the pollination of flowers. Flora 196 (1): 3 - 25." type="journal article" year="2001">Kastinger and Weber, 2001</bibRefCitation>
; Larsen et al., 2001; 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED194193FEA3CBEF750E" author="Orford, K. A. &amp; I. P. Vaughan &amp; J. Memmott" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 6" refId="ref60003" refString="Orford, K. A., I. P. Vaughan, and J. Memmott. 2015. The forgotten flies: the importance of non-syrphid Diptera as pollinators. Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B, Biological Sciences 282 (1805): 2014.2934 [1 - 6]." type="journal article" year="2015">Orford et al., 2015</bibRefCitation>
). They feed on nectar as well as pollen, many of them using a long proboscis to probe flowers; others have short proboscides. They are excellent hoverers. 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED19413CFE2CCAA87591" author="Yeates, D. K." box="[347,501,457,481]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 191" refId="ref61696" refString="Yeates, D. K. 1994. The cladistics and classification of the Bombyliidae (Diptera: Asiloidea). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 219: 1 - 191." type="journal article" year="1994">Yeates (1994)</bibRefCitation>
comprehensively analyzed the morphology and phylogeny of the 15 or so subfamilies, pruning the family of enigmatic genera traditionally placed in it, such as 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED1940F2FDA8CBA47615" box="[149,249,590,613]" class="Insecta" family="Scenopinidae" genus="Caenotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE928ED1940F2FDA8CBA47615" box="[149,249,590,613]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="64">Caenotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED194155FDA8CAD47615" authorityName="Melander" authorityYear="1906" box="[306,393,590,613]" class="Insecta" family="Scenopinidae" genus="Prorates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE928ED194155FDA8CAD47615" box="[306,393,590,613]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="64">Prorates</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(now in 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED19418AFDABC9DC7615" box="[493,641,589,613]" class="Insecta" family="Scenopinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scenopinidae</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED1940D6FD89CA6E76F6" authorityName="Melander" authorityYear="1950" box="[177,307,623,646]" class="Insecta" family="Apystomyiidae" genus="Apystomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE928ED1940D6FD89CA6E76F6" box="[177,307,623,646]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="64">Apystomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED194115FD88C94176F6" box="[370,540,622,646]" class="Insecta" family="Apystomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Apystomyiidae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED19425DFD89CBEC76D8" author="Yeates, D. K." pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 30" refId="ref61660" refString="Yeates, D. K. 1992. Towards a monophyletic Bombyliidae (Diptera): the removal of the Proratinae (Diptera: Scenopinidae). American Museum Novitates 3051: 1 - 30." type="journal article" year="1992">Yeates, 1992</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED1940A2FD69CA1276D7" authorityName=", sensu Yeates" authorityYear="1994" box="[197,335,655,679]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Bombyliidae</taxonomicName>
is at the base of the 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED194258FD69CBFD76B8" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" pageId="64" pageNumber="130" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Asiloidea">Asiloidea</taxonomicName>
, as either sister group to the 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED19418BFD56CBC3769A" class="Insecta" family="Hilarimorphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hilarimorphidae</taxonomicName>
—and this pair as sister group to all other asiloids (
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED1940BDFD15CA39777B" author="Yeates, D. K." box="[218,356,755,779]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 191" refId="ref61696" refString="Yeates, D. K. 1994. The cladistics and classification of the Bombyliidae (Diptera: Asiloidea). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 219: 1 - 191." type="journal article" year="1994">Yeates, 1994</bibRefCitation>
)—or itself as sister group to all other asiloids (
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED194136FCF2CAA8775C" author="Woodley, N. E." box="[337,501,788,812]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="1371 - 1395" refId="ref61466" refString="Woodley, N. E. 1989. Phylogeny and classification of the &quot; orthorrhaphous &quot; Brachycera. In J. F. McAlpine (editor), Manual of Nearctic Diptera. Volume 3: 1371 - 1395. Ottawa: Research Branch, Agriculture Canada." type="journal article" year="1989">Woodley, 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED194198FCF2C9D9775C" author="Yeates, D. K." box="[511,644,788,812]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="105 - 121" refId="ref61731" refString="Yeates, D. K. 2002. Relationships of extant lower Brachycera (Diptera): a quantitative synthesis of morphological characters. Zoologica Scripta 31 (1): 105 - 121." type="journal article" year="2002">Yeates, 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED19401FFCD3CA2B773D" author="Wiegmann, B. M." box="[120,374,821,845]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="5690 - 5695" refId="ref61142" refString="Wiegmann, B. M., et al. 2011. Episodic radiations in the fly tree of life. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America 108 (14): 5690 - 5695." type="journal article" year="2011">Wiegmann et al., 2011</bibRefCitation>
), or even as sister group to all other heterodactylan flies (
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED1941B0FCB0CBEC77FF" author="Trautwein, M. D. &amp; B. M. Wiegmann &amp; D. K. Yeates" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="918 - 930" refId="ref60833" refString="Trautwein, M. D., B. M. Wiegmann, and D. K. Yeates. 2010. A multigene phylogeny of the fly superfamily Asiloidea (Insecta): taxon sampling and additional genes reveal the sister-group to all higher flies (Cyclorrhapha). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 56 (3): 918 - 930." type="journal article" year="2010">Trautwein et al., 2010</bibRefCitation>
). The world species are cataloged (Evenhuis and Greathead, 1999, 2003).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0FAA6563E928ED1940FEFC5FCA877273" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" type="description">
<paragraph id="470F36E8E928ED1940FEFC5FCA877273" blockId="64.[119,650,226,1539]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64">
The Tertiary fossil record of 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED194182FC5FC93177A1" authorityName=", sensu Yeates" authorityYear="1994" box="[485,620,953,977]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Bombyliidae</taxonomicName>
is quite diverse, particularly as lithified remains in the larger shale deposits. The fossil record was reviewed by 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED1940FEFBFACA487044" author="Hull, F. M." box="[153,277,1052,1076]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" refId="ref58365" refString="Hull, F. M. 1973. Bee flies of the world: the genera of the family Bombyliidae. Washington: Smithsonian Institution Press." type="book" year="1973">Hull (1973)</bibRefCitation>
and Evenhuis (1994); more recent reports include 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED194148FBDBC90C7025" author="Nel, A. &amp; G. De Ploeg" box="[303,593,1085,1109]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="57 - 65" refId="ref59801" refString="Nel, A., and G. De Ploeg. 2004. New fossil bee flies (Diptera: Bombylioidea) in the lowermost Eocene amber of the Paris Basin. Geologica Acta 2 (1): 57 - 65." type="journal article" year="2004">Nel and de Plöeg (2004)</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED194205FBDBCBE27006" author="Nel, A." pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="109 - 114" refId="ref59733" refString="Nel, A. 2006. Oldest records of Bombyliidae: Phthiriinae and Mythicomyiidae: Glabellulinae from the Lowermost Eocene amber of France (Diptera: Bombylioidea). European Journal of Entomology 103 (1): 109 - 114." type="journal article" year="2006">Nel (2006)</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED1940AAFBB8C9507007" author="Wedmann, S. &amp; D. K. Yeates" box="[205,525,1118,1143]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="231 - 240" refId="ref61091" refString="Wedmann, S., and D. K. Yeates. 2008. Eocene records of bee flies (Insecta, Diptera, Bombyliidae, Comptosia): their palaeobiogeographic implications and remarks on the evolutionary history of bombyliids. Palaeontology 51 (1): 231 - 240." type="journal article" year="2008">Wedmann and Yeates (2008)</bibRefCitation>
. There is a substantial diversity of beeflies in Tertiary amber, including Cylleniinae in Baltic amber (
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED194257FB46CBF370AA" author="Hennig, W." pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 20" refId="ref58059" refString="Hennig, W. 1966. Bombyliidae im Kopal und im baltischen Bernstein (Diptera: Brachycera). Stuttgarter Beitrage fur Naturkunde 166: 1 - 20." type="journal article" year="1966">Hennig, 1966</bibRefCitation>
), and some 17 species of 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED1941D8FB24C93770AA" authorityName="Melander" authorityYear="1902" box="[447,618,1218,1242]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Mythicomyiinae">Mythicomyiinae</taxonomicName>
in Miocene Dominican amber and Eocene ambers from Europe (Baltic, Bitterfeld, Rovno, Oise) (Evenhuis, 2002, 2013). One of the few Cretaceous reports of beeflies is 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED194100FAA0C930712E" authority="Grimaldi" authorityName="Grimaldi" box="[359,621,1350,1374]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE928ED194100FAA0CAA3712E" box="[359,510,1350,1374]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="64">Microburmyia</emphasis>
Grimaldi
</taxonomicName>
, a putative stem-group mythicomyiine in amber from 
<collectingCountry id="3FA77678E928ED194010FA6FCBE271D0" box="[119,191,1417,1440]" name="Myanmar" pageId="64" pageNumber="64">Burma</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="23214B19E928ED1940AAFA6ECAFA71D0" author="Grimaldi, D. &amp; A. Arillo &amp; J. Cumming &amp; M. Hauser" box="[205,423,1416,1440]" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" pagination="293 - 332" refId="ref57883" refString="Grimaldi, D., A. Arillo, J. Cumming, and M. Hauser. 2011. Brachyceran Diptera (Insecta) in Cretaceous ambers, part IV: significant new orthorrhaphous taxa. Zookeys 148: 293 - 332." type="journal article" year="2011">Grimaldi et al., 2011</bibRefCitation>
). The four new 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED19422CFA6FCB9671B1" authorityName=", sensu Yeates" authorityYear="1994" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Bombyliidae</taxonomicName>
described here are, thus, important new records, especially since these are phylogenetically more derived than 
<taxonomicName id="80B04D6BE928ED194126FA0DCA8E7273" box="[321,467,1515,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Microburmyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75C4EAFAE928ED194126FA0DCA8E7273" box="[321,467,1515,1539]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="64">Microburmyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
